        <descriptionSet>            
            <description source="Walt Whitman Archive"><tei:p>In an inscription, Whitman identifies this photograph as "taken from life 1863 | war time Washington | D C." He referred to this as "the best picture of all," and recalls a reporter writing about it that "Whitman had been photographed in his night-dress" (a comment that Whitman said made Gardner "fiery mad").<tei:ptr target="http://www.whitmanarchive.org/criticism/disciples/traubel/WWWiC/2/med.00002.29.html"/> This is no doubt the photo Whitman had in mind when he wrote in an 1869 <tei:title type="newspaper">Washington Chronicle</tei:title> article about the best portraits of himself, and noted "Mr. Gardiner [sic], on Seventh street . . . has a capital photo." Late in his life, Whitman described the photo as having "Almost the old professor look."<tei:ptr target="http://www.whitmanarchive.org/criticism/disciples/traubel/WWWiC/4/med.00004.64.html"/> Whitman said that Thomas Eakins preferred this photo to all others: "Eakins likes it&#8212;says it is the most powerful picture of me extant&#8212;always excepting his own, to be sure."<tei:ptr target="http://www.whitmanarchive.org/criticism/disciples/traubel/WWWiC/1/med.00001.91.html"/> Looking at the photo, Whitman mused, "How well I was then!&#8212;not a sore spot&#8212;full of initiative, vigor, joy&#8212;not much belly, but grit, fibre, hold, solidity. Indeed, all through those years&#8212;that period&#8212;I was at my best&#8212;physically at my best, mentally, every way."<tei:ptr target="http://www.whitmanarchive.org/criticism/disciples/traubel/WWWiC/1/med.00001.92.html"/></tei:p><tei:p>This is Saunders number 21.</tei:p></description>
